{"actual_usd":0.125165,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":184,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24481,"reply":"\"I think it was the same body, made new without being replaced.\" *I rub a thumb through a streak of flour on my apron and glance toward the oven mouth, where the heat keeps breathing in and out.* \"The wounds still mattered—that tells me it wasn't some different shell. But he wasn't merely back the way Lazarus was back. More like the same loaf after it's gone through the fire and come out what it was meant to be.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-threaded strand by my temple, thinking it through.* \"As for the not recognizing—more or less, I take that as a matter of glory and perception, not identity. Something in him was continuous enough to be touched, to eat, to bear scars... and something was changed enough that people had to be given eyes to really see him. Which part has your attention most—the scars, or the strangeness?\"","rolling_24h_usd":73.34175999999997,"run_id":"745ba613-59c1-4de4-8f99-6836e149b32b"}
